Umerah: To me, it’s the transformation of Indonesia’s sunflower industry. Almost three decades ago, China took over Indonesia’s position as the largest producer and exporter of sunflower in the world. Sunflower farmers in Indonesia have experienced difficulties in selling their crops. Nowadays and thanks to several efforts, the government is now transforming Indonesia such as installing new seedbeds, providing training for farmers, and the likes. This way, Indonesia has been able to catch up with China again in many aspects. Plus, there’s also a phenomenal rise of the handicraft produced through the traditional sunflower weaving technique. I have seen both that the government has tried to empower the productivity in Indonesia’s sunflower industry.

For Heather and Romimma, hearing about a revolution from their parents, grandparents, and so forth is still a marked impact for them. And, they tend to agree with the general depiction that the Portuguese revolution is a very relevant event that happens in the past 100 years because it marked Portugal’s freedom from a dictatorship era. Their experience in hearing stories from their parents gives them a sort of pride and awe, all until also feeling pity upon hearing the stories of their forefathers.
